VLC in Docker with GUI + sound on Linux:

> mkdir soundcard-docker
> cd soundcard-docker

Step1 :
Dockerfile

FROM ubuntu:22.04

ENV DEBIAN_FRONTEND=noninteractive

# Install vlc, pulseaudio client, dbus, and utilities
RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y \
    vlc \
    pulseaudio \
    dbus-x11 \
    x11-utils \
    sudo \
    && apt-get clean

# Create user 'divya' with home directory, no password
RUN useradd -m divya && echo "divya ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: ALL" >> /etc/sudoers

USER divya
WORKDIR /home/divya

CMD ["vlc"]
____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
Step 2: Build the Docker image
docker build -t vlc-simple .
____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Step 3: Allow local docker containers to access X server
xhost +local:docker

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
Step 4: Run the container with GUI and audio support
Replace 1000 with your user ID if different (id -u):
docker run -it --rm \
    -e DISPLAY=$DISPLAY \
    -e PULSE_SERVER=unix:/run/user/1000/pulse/native \
    -v /tmp/.X11-unix:/tmp/.X11-unix \
    -v /run/user/1000/pulse/native:/run/user/1000/pulse/native \
    --device /dev/snd \
    --user $(id -u):$(id -g) \
    vlc-simple
_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Explanation:
> Runs VLC as non-root user divya inside container (with a proper home dir)
> Shares X11 socket to show VLC GUI on your host desktop
> Shares PulseAudio UNIX socket for audio output on your host
> Maps sound devices /dev/snd to allow ALSA passthrough if needed
> Uses your host user UID and GID to avoid permission issues with PulseAudio socket

_______________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
After the container starts, VLC GUI window should pop up on your desktop and audio will work through your host sound card.
